===Etymology 1===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{m|enm|hamme}}, from {{etyl|ang|en}} {{m|ang|hamm||inner or hind part of the knee, ham}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{m|gem-pro|*hamō}}, {{m|gem-pro|*hammō}}, {{m|gem-pro|*hanmō}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{m|ine-pro|*kanam-}}, {{m|ine-pro|*knāmā||thigh, shin}}. Cognate with Dutch {{m|nl|ham||ham}}, dialectal German {{m|de|Hamme||hind part of the knee, ham}}, dialectal {{etyl|sv|-}} {{m|sv|ham||the hind part of the knee}}, {{etyl|is|-}} {{m|is|höm||the ham or haunch of a horse}}, {{etyl|mga|-}} {{m|mga|cnáim||bone}}, {{etyl|grc|-}} {{m|grc|κνήμη||shinbone}}. Compare {{m|en|gammon}}.

